# PRD — The Signal: a newsreader for young students

**Status:** Clickable demo (v2) · **Owner:** TKEthics · **Last updated:** July 2026

## 1. Problem

Nowadays, the problem is that young students (middle and high school) are constantly surrounded by an overwhelming influx of digital content but rarely truly engage with real-world news. Adult news platforms are too dense, jargon-heavy, and dry, while alternative social feeds are highly algorithmic, fragmented, and dangerously unsourced. Most critically, nothing connects major current events back to the students' daily lives, personal interests, or classroom discussions. Consequently, students are graduating news-illiterate — unable to name credible sources, spot media bias, or articulate why a global or local event actually matters to them. Nowadays, the 
## 2. Goals

Help students understand what's happening in the real world on a daily basis.
Connect events to their lives by ensuring every story explicitly answers "why does this matter to me?"
Expose different perspectives to actively teach source and bias awareness.
Get students to question their own assumptions by prioritizing reason before results.
Let them share what's worth sharing directly within their close class community.
Support bilingual reading (EN/中文) and lightweight, contextual vocabulary learning.
Non-goals: breaking news speed; comprehensive or exhaustive news coverage; building an open social network (the community is strictly limited to the student's own classroom); traditional gamification points, leaderboards, or addictive streaks.

## 3. Audience

Primary: Students aged 11–16, primarily reading on mobile phones within short attention windows.
Secondary: Teachers who use the day's stories, polls, and metrics to seed meaningful classroom discussions.
